= section "The Infinitive" do
  %p The infinitive is the basic, unmarked form of the verb, lacking explicit marking for person, tense, and mood. It is also the citation form of verbs, and most verbs cited in this grammar will appear in the infinitive unless otherwise indicated. Unusually for a Romance language, the Tunisian infinitive has two forms, a singular and a plural.
  %p Conjugation I verbs form their infinitive by adding the suffix <i>-á</i> to the reduced stem.
  %p Conjugation II verbs form the infinitive with the suffix <i>-é</i> on the reduced stem.
  %p Conjugation III verbs form the infinitive one of the unstressed suffixes <i>-ey</i> or rarely <i>-y</i>. Which stems take which suffix cannot be predicted; the suffixes are arbitrarily associated with particular verbs. There is no ablaut in the stem.
  %p Conjugation IV verbs form the infinitive with the suffix <i>-í</i>. Reduction ablaut in generally not present, although a few particular subclasses will have it. In particular, verbs with a metathesizing /r/ will show reduction in the infinitive.
  %p Plurals for all conjugations are formed with the suffix <i>-s</i> /z/ added to the singular infinitive, sometimes with minor modifications to the singular stem. The first and second conjugations diphthongize the final vowel, becoming <i>-ays</i> and <i>-eys</i>. Third conjugation stems with a singular in <i>-y</i> become <i>-ís</i> in the plural. Other forms are regular.
